  "texts": [
    "Voter i holds prior beliefs b i about a binary, fixed state of the world θ ∈ {L, R} (e.g., whether the left-wing or rightwing candidate is a better fit for office).",
    "The cumulative density function (cdf) of the distribution of beliefs is denoted by H: [0, 1] → [0, 1] and describes the political leaning of the electorate, which we assume is symmetric about the median belief of 1/2 and non-degenerate (i.e., has density function h with h(α) = h(1 -α) for all α ∈ (0, 1)).",
    "We now introduce an order that captures the extent of polarization.",
    "An electorate described by H is more polarized than an electorate described by H (denoted by H ≻ H) if H-1 (α) > H -1 (α) for all α ∈ (1/2, 1) and H-1 (α) < H -1 (α) for all α ∈ (0, 1/2), with H-1 (1/2) = H -1 (1/2).",
    "In other words, our order means that H has the same median voter as H but is more spread out to the left and the right."
  ],
